Very busy writing the script for my review. Here is the first part:

The time has finally come!! OVERVIEW PROTEAMS

BINGOAL: Bingoal had a surprisingly good year in 2022, and as a result 14 (!) riders have made a transfer to another team. So they had to be very creative this transfer window, and have signed 11 new names so far. Guillaume VAN KEIRSBULCK wasn't needed anymore at Alpecin and could become a very good addition to this team. Floris DE TIER comes from Alpecin as well but he is shit. They also signed a few of the Sport Vlaanderen riders who aren't complete garbage, with Julian MERTENS and Kenneth VAN ROOY. Since Vlaanderen is a development team I thought these guys were young talents but Van Rooy is actually already 29. Strange. Some interesting names are Alexis GUERIN, who won a stage in SAZKA TOUR this year and was second place in IN THE FOOTSTEPS OF THE ROMANS!! And also Matteo MALUCELLI, a Mareczko-clone who raced a few months for China Glory, after the demise of Gazprom. Sovlful riders! Danish input comes from Alexander SALBY, another sprinter, who joins from Riwal. Aaron VAN DER BEKEN and Luca VAN BOVEN are joining from the Lotto u23 team, either they were shit or Lotto keeps getting screwed by every other team, which is pretty funny. I didn't think I was going to name everybody but sure why not, the last two are Nathan VANDEPITTE, who is French for some reason, and Lennert TEUGELS, a random shitter from Tarteletto. Interesting to see what Bingoal will do this year, with basically a whole new roster!

But the cult heroes like Aaron GATE and James FOUCHÉ have all stayed. Four other kiwis have joined, with Ollie JONES, Paul WRIGHT, Josh BURNETT and George JACKSON. No idea who these people are but I am sure it's great! Also three riders from WiV SunGod, who we all know very well from the Tour of Br*tain: Rory TOWNSEND, Matthew BOSTOCK and Jacob SCOTT. Some very good secret pick potential here.

BURGOS: Squeaking about secret picks, this team also has some nice ones: Manuel PEÑALVER and Ander OKAMIKA have made many Bert happy with their points. And let's not forget Victor LANGELOTTI, who shocked the world with a stage win in the VOLTA. They all stay, some shitters leave and some new riders are Antonio ANGULO, Clément ALLENO, Miguel Angel FERNANDEZ, Alejandro FRANCO (related to?) and Rodrigo ALVAREZ. Some of those may or may not exist. Eric Antonio FAGUNDEZ I do know, he raced the VOLTA this year for the very soulful Angolan team. He was a very very secret pick but basically did nothing there. Andres Camilo ARDILA joins too, after being at UAE for three years, but nobody noticed that. Finally the most well known name: Cyril BARTHE. A squeaky sort of sprinter who comes from B&B. I am fairly sure he is Basque so strange that Euskaltel didn't want him. Actually not so strange if you check his results.

EOLO-KOMETA: Finally the jokes can begin about Fernando TERCERO! Imagine if he gets another third place haha!! KERN PHARMA: I like this team better than Caja Rural. They have some pretty decent riders, and none of them left. Very impressive with retards like Will Barta and Juri Hollmann hanging around there. Mikel RETEGI and Pablo CASTRILLO are the other ones, who according to PCS made a transfer from team "?". 14 % des mariages célébrés en France en 2015 sont des mariages mixtes

Parmi les 236 300 mariages conclus en France en 2015, 33 800 ont uni une personne de nationalité étrangère et une personne de nationalité française (figure 1). Ces mariages mixtes (encadrés 1 et 2) représentent 14 % des mariages de l’année célébrés en France. Toujours en 2015, 9 100 couples de deux étrangers se sont mariés en France, soit 4 % de l’ensemble des célébrations. Ainsi, les mariages mixtes célébrés en France sont près de quatre fois plus nombreux que les mariages unissant deux personnes de nationalité étrangère.

Le nombre total de mariages célébrés en France a augmenté du milieu des années 1950 au début des années 1970. Il a ensuite reculé de manière quasi continue. Le nombre de mariages mixtes n’a pas suivi la même évolution : il a augmenté tendanciellement depuis le milieu des années 1950. Ainsi, les mariages mixtes prennent un poids croissant au sein de l’ensemble des mariages : leur part est passée de 6 % en 1950 à 14 % en 2015.

En 1994, le nombre de mariages mixtes retrouvait un niveau sensiblement équivalent à celui de la fin des années 1980, soit 23 300 mariages (9 % des célébrations de l’année).

Par la suite, les mariages mixtes deviennent à nouveau plus nombreux. Ils doublent entre 1994 et 2003, année record avec 47 500 célébrations (soit 17 % des mariages de l’année). Dès 2004, leur nombre décroît fortement et en 2010, 30 800 mariages mixtes sont célébrés en France (12 % des mariages de l’année), soit 16 700 de moins qu’en 2003.
La nationalité des conjoints à l’image des flux migratoires

En 2015, 12 500 mariages mixtes célébrés en France ont uni une personne de nationalité française à un conjoint d’une nationalité du Maghreb (Algérie, Maroc et Tunisie), soit 37 % des mariages mixtes de l’année (figures 2a à 2c). Suivent les unions entre Français et Européens avec 7 300 mariages mixtes (soit 22 %), puis celles entre Français et personnes de nationalité d’un pays d’Afrique sub-saharienne avec 4 900 mariages mixtes (soit 14 %).

La répartition des mariages mixtes célébrés en France par nationalité du conjoint étranger a fortement évolué depuis les années 1970. Les mariages entre Français et Italiens ou Espagnols étaient encore parmi les plus nombreux à la fin des années 1970 : en 1977, ils représentaient près du tiers (31 %) des mariages mixtes. Leur importance a fortement baissé dans les années 1980 et depuis 2002, moins de 1 500 mariages mixtes impliquant une personne de nationalité espagnole ou italienne sont célébrés chaque année. En 2015, ces mariages ne représentent plus que 4 % des mariages mixtes.

Les mariages mixtes impliquant une nationalité du Maghreb (Algérie, Maroc ou Tunisie) ont connu deux pics importants. Ils ont tout d’abord augmenté rapidement à partir de la fin des années 1980. En 1987, 5 700 mariages mixtes concernaient une personne de nationalité algérienne, tunisienne ou marocaine, soit 27 % des mariages mixtes célébrés cette année-là ; quatre ans après, en 1991, leur nombre avait plus que doublé, pour atteindre 12 900 mariages, soit 39 % des mariages mixtes de l’année. Il s’est réduit par la suite avant de connaître une nouvelle hausse pour atteindre 20 900 mariages en 2003, soit 44 % des mariages mixtes de l’année célébrés en France. Le nombre de mariages impliquant une personne de nationalité autre que maghrébine a connu à peu près les mêmes fluctuations.

Ces évolutions traduisent en partie celles des flux migratoires. Après la deuxième guerre mondiale, l’immigration provenait essentiellement des pays européens : Italie et Espagne notamment. Les migrants portugais sont arrivés un peu plus tardivement, dans les années 1960 et 1970. L’immigration algérienne a progressé après-guerre, alors que celle provenant du Maroc a débuté un peu plus tard, dans les années 1970. Dans les années 1980, l’éventail des origines s’est ouvert aux autres pays d’Afrique, d’Asie et d’Europe.

The passing of Sinisa Mihajlovic made me realize how appreciated he was; he certainly wasn't among the best defensive players of his era, but his unusual skillset and temperament obviously made him one of sport's mavericks. Today I was thinking about the unfortunate tribalism that followed both his life and passing - born in Croatia, he achieved fame just as war was starting, and it started exactly in the small village where his family lived. So there has been a lot of slander from Croatian side, a nation whose statehood is identified with a Nazi puppet state with concentration camps for children; wars of the 90s dredged up the worst from the past so when people like Sinisa expressed what they thought about the rise of the same type of nationalism that was still well-remembered in the parts of Croatia where he was born (and from which 300 000 Serbs were cleansed a few years later, which they celebrated during the Canada game, as the goalkeeper was a child when he was forced to flee for his life alongside his family), he became a target. You cannot bring the sanctity of that war into question, the same way you can't look at Croatian flags in this WC and see that more than half of them have a white square in the topmost corner - the symbol of the aforementioned slaughter state.

I have similalrly scathing view of Serbian nationalism, but I'm typing this out because I was reminded of this when he passed. Mihajlovic is the prime example of why perfidious nations such as British ruled the world - they were always about cultural imperialism and narrative control. He was often an uncouth, passionate figure who perhaps did not quite grasp the entire picture (and associated with Arkan to some extent) and this made him a prime propaganda target. I believe that is both a tragedy of his life and a testament to his character. Even dumb jocks have soul. To whom it may concern etc.

Imagine that each country is a team in a big sports league. Just like how different sports teams have their own coaches, players, and rules, each country has its own government, people, and laws.

Just like how sports teams work together to play games and compete with each other, countries work together to solve problems and interact with each other. This is what we call "foreign policy."

Each country has its own goals and interests, just like how each sports team has its own strategies and goals for winning games. And just like how sports teams have to follow certain rules and respect each other on the field, countries have to follow certain rules and respect each other in the world.

Sometimes, countries might have conflicts or disagreements, just like how sports teams might have rivalries or arguments. But just like how sports teams try to resolve their conflicts and find ways to work together, countries try to find ways to resolve their conflicts and work together as well.

This shit pisses me the FUCK OFF.
The closest star to the sun is 4.25 light years away. That's 4.25 years of travelling at the speed of light just to get there.
Fastest a human made object has ever been is 330,000 mph (the Parker Space probe which flew close to the sun).

Now ignoring the fact that used the sun's STRONG gravitational pull, let's just say against all reason we maintain that velocity going towards the next solar system.

Speed = Distance/Time
Time = Distance/Speed
2.4984e+13 = 4.25 light years in miles

2.4984e+13/330,000 = 75709090.9091 hours = 8642 years.
But that's adding in the strong gravitational pull offered by the sun, completely ignoring how we'd have only our batteries to rely on within the vast emptiness of space.

THEN consider the fact that Alpha Centauri doesn't even hold the possibility for life - it's just how far you have to go for another planet.

Humanity will never ever ever experience space travel outside of our solar system.
Don't know why we invest so much time thinking about it desu.

>what was the game (world cup?) where the end came down to the "shootout" and the nogs fucked it up?
England vs Italy, Euro 2020 final last year. The Euros are a continental tournament held every 4 years and organized by UEFA (European confederation). Only Europeans teams were allowed to webm related
>when will the next world cup be?
June-July 2026, hosted in US, Mexico and Canada (16 different cities). Because it's hosted in those 3 countries, they're automatically qualified for the tournament, Hosts don't ever have to qualify.

As for the rest qualifying, Asia, Africa, Europe, Oceania, it usually takes like 1-2 years of playing against other teams from the continent they're in to determine whether or not they qualify for the WC. Because it's 4 years away, most of these matches and group qualifiers haven't been determined yet.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2026_FIFA_World_Cup_qualification

>>127283595
Yes, the World Cup is held every 4 years, that's why every single WC is coveted so much by all the participating players and countries. Most of the footballers do not maintain such a high level during their career that they get selected for their national team (only the best 26 players can be chosen for a national team). Most players play in like 1, 2 and if you're a very good player 3 WC's in their career or even more.

Here's a short list of countries the WC was held in:
>2026: Canada, United States (2nd time), Mexico (3rd time)
>2022: Qatar
>2018: Russia
>2014: Brazil
>2010: South Africa
>2006: Germany (2nd time)
>2002: Japan/South Korea
>1998: France (2nd time)
>1994: United States
>1990: Italy (2nd time)
>1986: Mexico

I'm not 100% sure on how the bidding process for each WC goes, but I believe different countries can put in a bid to hold the WC in their country, but joint bids are also possible like America, Canada and Mexico for 2026. Morocco also put in a bid for 2026, but they lost out to you guys. That's probably because the people who voted think that there will most likely be less problems, because your countries are more stable. Bids for 2030 aren't known yet. A funny one is the proposed joint bid by Israel, UAE and Bahrain.

it's the united kingdom of great britain and northern ireland, there is no "kingdoms", the entire thing is a kingdom.
